 {"id":"bd-320","title":"Integrate rich logging into FastMCP server startup","description":"## Purpose and Rationale

Wire the RichTracingSubscriber into FastMCP's server startup path so that all logging throughout the server lifecycle displays with rich formatting. This is the integration point that makes all the logging work visible.

## Background

FastMCP servers are typically started via Server::run_stdio(). This is the ideal location to initialize the rich tracing subscriber because:
1. It happens early enough to capture all logs
2. We have access to configuration
3. We can detect the display context (agent vs human)

## Technical Specification

### Integration Point

```rust
// crates/fastmcp/src/server.rs

impl Server {
    pub async fn run_stdio(self) -> Result<(), Error> {
        // NEW: Initialize rich logging early
        self.init_rich_logging()?;

        // Existing startup banner (from Phase 2)
        self.display_startup_banner();

        // Rest of existing implementation...
        let (stdin, stdout) = (io::stdin(), io::stdout());
        // ...
    }

    fn init_rich_logging(&self) -> Result<(), Error> {
        use fastmcp_console::logging::RichSubscriberBuilder;

        // Get configuration from server config or environment
        let log_level = self.config.log_level.unwrap_or(LevelFilter::INFO);
        let show_timestamps = self.config.log_timestamps.unwrap_or(true);

        // Build and initialize subscriber
        RichSubscriberBuilder::new()
            .with_level_filter(log_level)
            .with_timestamps(show_timestamps)
            .with_theme(self.console_theme.clone())
            .init()
            .map_err(|e| Error::Internal(format\!("Failed to init logging: {}", e)))?;

        tracing::debug\!("Rich logging initialized");
        Ok(())
    }
}
```

### Configuration Options

Add logging configuration to server config:

```rust
// crates/fastmcp/src/config.rs

pub struct ServerConfig {
    // Existing fields...

    /// Logging configuration
    pub logging: LoggingConfig,
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone, Default)]
pub struct LoggingConfig {
    /// Minimum log level (default: INFO)
    pub level: Option<LevelFilter>,

    /// Show timestamps in logs (default: true)
    pub timestamps: bool,

    /// Show module targets in logs (default: true)  
    pub targets: bool,

    /// Show file:line in logs (default: false)
    pub file_line: bool,

    /// Custom theme override
    pub theme: Option<FastMcpTheme>,
}
```

### Environment Variable Support

Honor standard logging environment variables:

```rust
impl LoggingConfig {
    pub fn from_env() -> Self {
        Self {
            level: std::env::var("FASTMCP_LOG")
                .ok()
                .and_then(|s| s.parse().ok()),
            timestamps: std::env::var("FASTMCP_LOG_TIMESTAMPS")
                .map(|s| s \!= "0" && s.to_lowercase() \!= "false")
                .unwrap_or(true),
            // ... etc
        }
    }
}
```

### Fallback Behavior

If rich logging init fails, fall back to standard tracing:

```rust
fn init_rich_logging(&self) -> Result<(), Error> {
    match RichSubscriberBuilder::new()
        .with_level_filter(log_level)
        .init() 
    {
        Ok(()) => Ok(()),
        Err(e) => {
            // Fall back to standard fmt subscriber
            eprintln\!("Warning: Rich logging unavailable: {}", e);
            tracing_subscriber::fmt()
                .with_max_level(log_level)
                .with_writer(std::io::stderr)
                .init();
            Ok(())
        }
    }
}
```

## Implementation Steps

1. Add LoggingConfig to ServerConfig struct
2. Implement from_env() for environment variable parsing
3. Add init_rich_logging() method to Server
4. Call init_rich_logging() early in run_stdio()
5. Add fallback to standard tracing on failure
6. Update Server builder to accept logging config
7. Add integration tests

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Rich logging initializes before any log output
- [ ] Configuration is respected (level, timestamps, etc)
- [ ] Environment variables override defaults
- [ ] Fallback works if rich logging fails
- [ ] No interference with JSON-RPC on stdout
- [ ] All server logs display with rich formatting
- [ ] Integration tests verify log output

## Testing Strategy

```rust
#[tokio::test]
async fn test_server_logging_initialization() {
    let server = Server::new("test")
        .with_logging(LoggingConfig {
            level: Some(LevelFilter::DEBUG),
            ..Default::default()
        });

    // Capture stderr and verify rich formatting
}
```

